TY  - JOUR
T1  - Market Structure and Competition in Airline Markets
AU  - Ciliberto, Federico
AU  - Murry, Charles
AU  - Tamer, Elie
Y1  - 2021/06/11
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/715848
DO  - 10.1086/715848
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2995
EP  - 3038
VL  - 129
IS  - 11
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We provide an econometric framework for estimating a game of simultaneous entry and pricing decisions while allowing for correlations between unobserved cost and demand shocks. We use our framework to account for selection in the pricing stage. We estimate the model using data from the US airline industry and find that not accounting for endogenous entry leads to biased estimation of demand elasticities. We simulate a merger between American and US Airways and find that product repositioning and postmerger outcomes depend on how we model the characteristics of the merged firm as a function of the premerger firms? characteristics.
AB  - We provide an econometric framework for estimating a game of simultaneous entry and pricing decisions while allowing for correlations between unobserved cost and demand shocks. We use our framework to account for selection in the pricing stage. We estimate the model using data from the US airline industry and find that not accounting for endogenous entry leads to biased estimation of demand elasticities. We simulate a merger between American and US Airways and find that product repositioning and postmerger outcomes depend on how we model the characteristics of the merged firm as a function of the premerger firms? characteristics.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/715848
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/715848
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Directed Technical Change as a Response to Natural Resource Scarcity
AU  - Hassler, John
AU  - Krusell, Per
AU  - Olovsson, Conny
Y1  - 2021/06/11
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/715849
DO  - 10.1086/715849
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3039
EP  - 3072
VL  - 129
IS  - 11
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We develop a quantitative macroeconomic theory of input-saving technical change to analyze how markets economize on scarce natural resources, with an application to fossil fuel. We find that aggregate US data call for a very low short-run substitution elasticity between energy and the capital/labor inputs. Our estimates imply that energy-saving technical change took off when the oil shocks hit in the 1970s. This response implies significant substitutability with the other inputs in the long run: even under ever-rising energy prices, long-run consumption growth is still possible, along with a modest factor share of energy.
AB  - We develop a quantitative macroeconomic theory of input-saving technical change to analyze how markets economize on scarce natural resources, with an application to fossil fuel. We find that aggregate US data call for a very low short-run substitution elasticity between energy and the capital/labor inputs. Our estimates imply that energy-saving technical change took off when the oil shocks hit in the 1970s. This response implies significant substitutability with the other inputs in the long run: even under ever-rising energy prices, long-run consumption growth is still possible, along with a modest factor share of energy.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/715849
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/715849
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Power of Referential Advice
AU  - Callander, Steven
AU  - Lambert, Nicolas S.
AU  - Matouschek, Niko
Y1  - 2021/06/11
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/715850
DO  - 10.1086/715850
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3073
EP  - 3140
VL  - 129
IS  - 11
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Expert advice often extends beyond a simple recommendation, including information about alternative options. To explore the role of this referential advice, we enrich the expert?s informational advantage in a canonical model of communication with hard information. We show that when constructed just right, referential advice dissuades the decision maker from choosing options other than the recommendation, thereby making the recommendation itself more persuasive. We identify an equilibrium in which, with probability 1, the expert is strictly better off providing referential advice than she is in any equilibrium in which she provides a recommendation alone.
AB  - Expert advice often extends beyond a simple recommendation, including information about alternative options. To explore the role of this referential advice, we enrich the expert?s informational advantage in a canonical model of communication with hard information. We show that when constructed just right, referential advice dissuades the decision maker from choosing options other than the recommendation, thereby making the recommendation itself more persuasive. We identify an equilibrium in which, with probability 1, the expert is strictly better off providing referential advice than she is in any equilibrium in which she provides a recommendation alone.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/715850
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/715850
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Optimal Income Taxation: Mirrlees Meets Ramsey
AU  - Heathcote, Jonathan
AU  - Tsujiyama, Hitoshi
Y1  - 2021/06/11
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/715851
DO  - 10.1086/715851
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3141
EP  - 3184
VL  - 129
IS  - 11
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We explore the optimal shape of the income tax and transfer schedule in an environment with distinct roles for public and private insurance. In a calibration to the United States, we find that the optimal system features marginal tax rates that increase in income. When we increase pressure on the government to raise revenue, the optimal marginal tax schedule becomes first flatter and then U-shaped, reconciling various findings in the literature. A power function parametric tax schedule outperforms an affine one, indicating that tax progressivity is more important than lump-sum transfers. We also explore various social welfare objectives and Pareto-improving reforms.
AB  - We explore the optimal shape of the income tax and transfer schedule in an environment with distinct roles for public and private insurance. In a calibration to the United States, we find that the optimal system features marginal tax rates that increase in income. When we increase pressure on the government to raise revenue, the optimal marginal tax schedule becomes first flatter and then U-shaped, reconciling various findings in the literature. A power function parametric tax schedule outperforms an affine one, indicating that tax progressivity is more important than lump-sum transfers. We also explore various social welfare objectives and Pareto-improving reforms.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/715851
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/715851
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Comparison of Decisions under Unknown Experiments
AU  - Caplin, Andrew
AU  - Martin, Daniel
Y1  - 2021/06/25
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/716104
DO  - 10.1086/716104
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3185
EP  - 3205
VL  - 129
IS  - 11
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We take the perspective of an econometrician who wants to determine which of two experiments provides higher expected utility but only knows the decisions under each experiment. To compare these decisions, the econometrician must make inferences about what the experiment might have been for each set of decisions. We provide a necessary and sufficient condition that identifies when every experiment consistent with one set of decisions has a higher value of information than every experiment consistent with the other set of decisions.
AB  - We take the perspective of an econometrician who wants to determine which of two experiments provides higher expected utility but only knows the decisions under each experiment. To compare these decisions, the econometrician must make inferences about what the experiment might have been for each set of decisions. We provide a necessary and sufficient condition that identifies when every experiment consistent with one set of decisions has a higher value of information than every experiment consistent with the other set of decisions.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/716104
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/716104
Y2  - 2024/03/20
